so its actually pretty simple 
in c you have the stdlib library which gives you calloc 

calloc works the same as malloc, but it makes sure all bits are 0

in assembly you have the same thing but its with uninitalized data

so for example you need to reserve some memory for some kind of data 
as an example we create a list of integers 

in a good world we would use int bobo[3]
but in asm its a bit different

so we can infact declare uninitalized data this way, we would use a section called .bss
section .bss
    uninitalized_list resb 3 ; where resb = reserve-byte

so in our case we would have 3 slots.
Visually: [0,0,0]

Indexing in asm works too, but its again a bit different. 
so when we would like to get and replace the 0 in the middle with another number (viusally!)
we would do 
    mov bl, 1;
    mov [uninitalized_list+1], bl ;

where uninitalized_list+1 is basically uninitalized_list[1].
same thing. but its a bit raw. imagine 0+1 = 1. thats about it. 



